{
  "text": "In the field experiment described in this paper, we used a profiler to collect temperature microstructure profiles at both shallow and deep sites. The profiler descended through the water column until a weightrelease switch was activated at the required depth and sampling began. The profiler sampled at 100 Hz and ascended the water column at 10 cm S-', giving a spatial resolution of g 1 mm for temperature and conductivity. The profiler was identical to that described by [CITATION_1] but without the dissolved oxygen sensor. The method for the estimation of dissipation from the temperature gradient spectra is described in Imberger & Ivey (1991).",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "94959109"
  },
  "bib_entries": {
    "94959109": {
      "title": "A fast-response oxygen sensor for use on finescale and microstructure CTD profilers",
      "abstract": "A specialized oxygen sensor is described whose fast response times make it ideal for studies of the effects of mixing processes on oxygen concentrations. A polarographic oxygen microelectrode was installed on a microstructure CTD profiler. The oxygen microelectrode has a tip size of 30 \u03bcm, a total length of 5 cm, membrane thickness of < 4 \u03bcm, and a time constant of 0.13 s. Flow dependence is minimal, and the amplifying and conditioning electronics are installed inside the body of the profiler, which is 50 cm long and 10 cm in diameter. The profiler samples temperature, gradient temperature, conductivity, dissolved oxygen, and pressure as it ascends through the water column at 10 cm s \u22121 . Sampling at 100 Hz allows temperature, conductivity, and depth measurements every 1 mm and dissolved oxygen measurements every 1.3 cm"
    }
  }
}